# Lab 04 — TCP vs UDP Traffic Capture & Port Analysis

**Track:** CompTIA Network+ Self-Study  
**Topic:** TCP/UDP Protocol Behavior, Three-Way Handshake, DNS, Port States  
**Tools:** `tcpdump`, `netstat`  
**Environment:** Parrot OS (Linux), wireless interface `wlo1`

---

## Objectives

- Capture and analyze a real TCP three-way handshake using `tcpdump`
- Capture live UDP traffic (DNS queries/responses)
- Identify listening services on the local machine
- Identify which ports active established connections are using

---

## LAB 1 TCP Three-Way Handshake Capture

### Command

```bash
sudo tcpdump -i any -n 'tcp[tcpflags] & (tcp-syn|tcp-ack) != 0' -c 6 -w tcp-handshake.pcap
tcpdump -r tcp-handshake.pcap -n
```

**Flag breakdown:**
| Flag | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `-i any` | Capture on all interfaces |
| `-n` | Don't resolve hostnames (show raw IPs) |
| `tcp[tcpflags] & (tcp-syn\|tcp-ack) != 0` | Filter for SYN and ACK flags only |
| `-c 6` | Stop after 6 packets |
| `-w` | Write to `.pcap` file |

### Captured Output

```
14:48:12.665403 wlo1  Out  10.176.129.248.58288 > 20.207.73.82.443: Flags [S]   ← SYN
14:48:13.072880 wlo1  In   20.207.73.82.443 > 10.176.129.248.58288: Flags [S.]  ← SYN-ACK
14:48:13.072967 wlo1  Out  10.176.129.248.58288 > 20.207.73.82.443: Flags [.]   ← ACK
14:48:13.074347 wlo1  Out  10.176.129.248.58288 > 20.207.73.82.443: Flags [P.]  ← Data push (TLS ClientHello)
14:48:13.279893 wlo1  In   20.207.73.82.443 > 10.176.129.248.58288: Flags [P.]  ← Server response (2526 bytes)
14:48:13.279979 wlo1  Out  10.176.129.248.58288 > 20.207.73.82.443: Flags [.]   ← ACK
```

### Analysis

The capture shows a complete TCP three-way handshake to **20.207.73.82 on port 443** (Microsoft Azure — likely a background HTTPS connection):

```
Client                          Server
  |------- SYN ----------------->|   seq=1454338903
  |<------ SYN-ACK --------------|   seq=464753183, ack=1454338904
  |------- ACK ----------------->|   ack=1
  
  [Handshake complete — connection established]
  
  |------- DATA (399 bytes) ---->|   TLS ClientHello
  |<------ DATA (2526 bytes) ----|   TLS ServerHello + Certificate
  |------- ACK ----------------->|
```

**Key observations:**
- RTT (SYN → SYN-ACK): ~407ms — indicates a remote server, not LAN
- Destination port 443 = HTTPS (encrypted traffic)
- `[P.]` flag = PSH+ACK (data being pushed, not just acknowledged)
- Window scaling negotiated: client `wscale 7` (×128), server `wscale 10` (×1024)
- MSS: client advertises 1460 bytes, server advertises 1275 bytes (lower due to network path)

