## Lab 2 — UDP Traffic Capture (DNS)

### Command

```bash
sudo tcpdump -i any udp port 53 -c 5 -w udp-traffic.pcap
tcpdump -r udp-traffic.pcap -n
```

**Port 53 = DNS** — UDP is used for standard DNS queries (connectionless, no handshake).

### Captured Output

```
14:50:22.085825  Out  10.176.129.248.59444 > 10.176.129.9.53:  38494+ A? gemini.google.com.
14:50:22.310185  In   10.176.129.9.53 > 10.176.129.248.59444:  38494 8/0/0 A 142.251.150.2, ...
14:50:22.310497  Out  10.176.129.248.35939 > 10.176.129.9.53:  20817+ AAAA? gemini.google.com.
14:50:22.315675  In   10.176.129.9.53 > 10.176.129.248.35939:  20817 Refused 0/0/0
14:50:28.431523  Out  10.176.129.248.37391 > 10.176.129.9.53:  24108+ A? github.com.
```

### Analysis

| # | Direction | Query | Result |
|---|-----------|-------|--------|
| 1 | Out | `A` record for `gemini.google.com` | → DNS resolver at 10.176.129.9 |
| 2 | In | Response | 8 IPv4 addresses returned (load balanced) |
| 3 | Out | `AAAA` record for `gemini.google.com` (IPv6) | → same resolver |
| 4 | In | Response | **REFUSED** — IPv6 not supported by this resolver |
| 5 | Out | `A` record for `github.com` | (response not captured within 5-packet limit) |

**Key observations:**
- DNS server: **10.176.129.9** (local gateway/router acting as resolver)
- `A?` = asking for IPv4 address; `AAAA?` = asking for IPv6
- The `+` after query ID means recursion desired (RD flag set)
- UDP has **no handshake** — query goes out, answer comes back, done
- Transaction IDs (`38494`, `20817`) are used to match replies to queries
- RTT for DNS: ~225ms (first query to response)

**TCP vs UDP contrast visible in this lab:**

| | TCP (HTTPS) | UDP (DNS) |
|--|-------------|-----------|
| Connection setup | 3-way handshake | None |
| Reliability | Guaranteed delivery | Best-effort |
| State tracking | Yes (seq/ack numbers) | No |
| Use case | File transfer, web, SSH | DNS, DHCP, streaming |

